<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Color Spectrum for Quality Assessment</strong> - The hue of rosé tells you everything about production method and grape variety. Pale salmon-pink indicates direct press or saignée method with minimal skin contact, perfect for delicate Provence-style wines. Deeper coral or onion-skin colors suggest longer maceration or specific grapes like Grenache or Sangiovese. Avoid any rosé with orange or brown tinges, which indicate oxidation or age-related deterioration.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 45-50°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike red wines, rosé's delicate aromatics and crisp acidity shine when properly chilled. Too cold (below 40°F) and you'll mute the subtle strawberry and white peach notes; too warm (above 55°F) and the wine becomes flabby and loses its refreshing character. Place bottles in the refrigerator 2-3 hours before serving, or use an ice bucket for 20 minutes.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter - Rosé Needs No Aeration</strong> - Rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment and their delicate fruit flavors can actually be stripped away by excessive oxygen exposure. Pour directly from bottle to glass to preserve the wine's fresh, vibrant character. The only exception is vintage Champagne rosé, which may benefit from gentle swirling in the glass to release complex brioche and red fruit aromatics.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose White Wine Glasses Over Red for Better Aromatics</strong> - Use a smaller bowl white wine glass rather than a large red wine glass. Rosé's subtle aromatics - think wild strawberries, white flowers, and citrus zest - concentrate better in a narrower opening. Avoid flutes unless drinking sparkling rosé, as the restricted surface area limits the wine's ability to express its full aromatic complexity.</li>

  <li><strong>Follow the "Drink Young" Rule with Strategic Exceptions</strong> - Most still rosés should be consumed within 18 months of vintage date to capture their peak freshness. However, premium rosés from Bandol, Tavel, or Sancerre can evolve beautifully for 3-5 years, developing honeyed notes and mineral complexity. Vintage rosé Champagne can age gracefully for 8-10 years, gaining toasty, brioche-like characteristics.</li>

  <li><strong>Read the Back Label for Residual Sugar Clues</strong> - Many rosés contain 2-8 grams per liter of residual sugar to enhance their approachable character, but this isn't always obvious. Look for terms like "sec" (dry), "off-dry," or check the alcohol level - wines below 12% ABV often retain more residual sugar. Bone-dry rosés from Provence typically show 13-14% alcohol with less than 2g/L residual sugar.</li>

