<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike red wines, most rosés are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential is crucial for maximizing your collection's value and pleasure.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Light, fruit-forward rosés</strong> (Provence-style, Pinot Grigio rosato) peak within 1-2 years, as their delicate aromatics and crisp acidity begin to fade. <strong>Structured rosés</strong> from quality producers like Bandol's Mourvèdre-based wines or Champagne rosé can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, gaining complexity while maintaining freshness.</p>

<p><strong>Premium rosé Champagne</strong> represents the category's aging champion, with vintage bottlings from houses like Billecart-Salmon developing tertiary notes of brioche and honey over 8-12 years while retaining their signature elegance.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>
<p>Young rosés showcase bright red fruit—strawberry, raspberry, watermelon—with pronounced floral notes. As they mature, these primary aromatics evolve into more complex profiles featuring dried herbs, subtle spice, and mineral undertones. The wine's texture typically softens as the phenolic structure integrates.</p>

<p>Most rosés should be consumed within their first vintage year for optimal fruit expression, though quality examples can maintain appeal through their second year when stored properly.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store rosé at consistent <strong>50-55°F</strong> with 70% humidity, away from light and vibration. Unlike age-worthy reds, rosés benefit from slightly cooler storage to preserve their delicate fruit character. Keep bottles horizontal to maintain cork moisture.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged rosé develops honeyed notes and deeper color saturation while maintaining structural balance. <strong>Warning signs of decline</strong> include browning (beyond natural evolution), loss of fruit intensity, flat aromatics, or vinegar-like sharpness indicating bacterial spoilage. When in doubt, consume sooner rather than later—rosé's charm lies in its youthful vibrancy.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between dry and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosés contain less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter and showcase pure fruit flavors without sweetness, while sweet rosés like White Zinfandel can contain 15-45 grams per liter. The key indicator is the wine's origin - European rosés (Provence, Loire Valley, Spanish Rosado) are typically bone dry, whereas many American rosés lean toward off-dry or sweet. You can also check the alcohol level: dry rosés usually range from 11.5-13.5% ABV, while sweeter versions often fall below 11%.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should rosé wine be served ice-cold like white wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé should be served chilled but not ice-cold - the ideal temperature is 45-50°F (7-10°C), slightly warmer than most white wines. Over-chilling mutes the delicate fruit flavors and aromatics that make rosé special, while serving it too warm emphasizes alcohol and can make it taste flabby. Remove the bottle from the refrigerator about 10-15 minutes before serving, or aim for the temperature of a well-chilled white Burgundy.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can you keep an opened bottle of rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of rosé will maintain its fresh, crisp character for 3-5 days when properly stored in the refrigerator with a wine stopper or vacuum seal. Unlike red wines, rosé doesn't benefit from extended air exposure and will lose its vibrant fruit flavors quickly once oxidation begins. The high acidity in most rosés helps preserve them longer than low-acid wines, but delicate Provence-style rosés may start declining after just 2-3 days.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value rosé wine region for everyday drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Loire Valley rosés, particularly Rosé d'Anjou and Cabernet d'Anjou, offer exceptional value with authentic French character at $12-18 per bottle. Spanish Rosado from regions like Navarra and Campo de Borja provide robust, food-friendly options at similar price points with more body than typical Provence styles. For domestic options, Washington State rosés deliver excellent quality-to-price ratios, often outperforming similarly priced California bottlings with better acidity and more refined fruit expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibored text-wine-700 mb-2">Why does some rosé taste like candy while others taste bone dry?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The difference lies in winemaking technique and regional traditions - European rosés undergo complete fermentation converting all grape sugars to alcohol, while many American rosés are stopped mid-fermentation to retain residual sugar. Additionally, some producers add grape concentrate or use specific yeast strains that emphasize fruity esters, creating a "candied" perception even in technically dry wines. Grape variety also matters: Grenache and Cinsault create elegant, dry styles while White Zinfandel grapes naturally produce sweeter, more confected flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine good for beginners who don't like red or white wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is perfect for wine beginners because it bridges the gap between whites and reds with approachable fruit flavors, moderate acidity, and no tannins to create astringency. The visual appeal and food versatility make it less intimidating than complex reds, while the dry styles offer more sophistication than sweet starter wines. Start with a Provence rosé or Spanish Rosado to experience the style at its most refined, then explore different grape varieties and regions to develop your palate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is buying rosé from previous vintages - unlike red wines, rosé is meant to be consumed within 1-2 years of the vintage date to capture its fresh, vibrant character. Many retailers sell discounted older rosés that have lost their bright acidity and primary fruit flavors, leaving behind flat, oxidized wines that misrepresent the category. Always check the vintage date and choose the most recent year available, especially for delicate styles like Provence rosé.</p>
